% ---------------- METHODOLOGY ----------------
\newpage
\section{Methodology}
\noindent
The development of this system will follow the Incremental Model of the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) where the system is built and improved in multiple small modules (increments).Each increment adds new features while keeping previously developed parts fully functional. The process begins with requirement analysis, identifying the need for smart home automation,smart parking, and safety monitoring.

\subsection{Software Development Life Cycle}

\begin{figure}[H]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{Incremental.png}
    \caption{Incremental Model}
    \label{fig:sample}
\end{figure}
\newpage
\subsection{System Architecture}
\noindent
The proposed AI system integrates IoT sensing, cloud storage, and machine learning to deliver real-time predictions for both energy consumption and parking availability. The system follows a multi-layer architecture consisting of an edge sensing layer (ESP32), communication layer (Wi-Fi), backend gateway/API layer, database layer, AI/ML processing layer, and application layer (mobile dashboard).\\
At the sensing layer, the ESP32 collects real-time readings from parking sensors (HC-SR04 ultrasonic distance sensors per slot) and optional environmental sensors such as DHT11. The energy module uses either energy sensor readings (power/energy measurements) or a historical dataset captured from appliance usage logs. Raw readings are preprocessed at the edge to reduce noise (e.g., averaging ultrasonic distance values) and then transmitted over Wi-Fi using HTTP/MQTT or through Blynk connectivity.\\
In the backend layer, the API gateway validates incoming data, stores readings in the database, and forwards relevant features to the ML inference service. The database maintains raw sensor values, engineered features, and prediction logs to support both model training and monitoring.\\
The AI layer includes two machine learning models: (1) a Linear Regression model for predicting continuous energy consumption values (kWh/power), and (2) a Random Forest Classifier for predicting parking slot status (occupied/free). Linear Regression is used due to its simplicity and interpretability for energy prediction, while Random Forest is chosen for parking classification because it is robust to noisy sensor readings and can model non-linear decision boundaries.\\
Finally, the mobile application (Flutter) and dashboard (Blynk) display real-time sensor values and predictions to users. The system supports continuous operation where new data is logged, predictions are generated instantly, and the UI is updated accordingly.

\newpage
\subsection{AI System Architecture}

\noindent\textbf{1. Home Automation and Smart Infrastructure}

\begin{itemize}
    
    \item An energy optimization engine utilizing the Linear Regression model to predict power consumption and enable efficient load management.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{2. Perception \& IoT Data Layer}

This layer consists of the hardware and sensors deployed within the home and parking area:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Energy Monitoring Subsystem:} Smart meters and current sensors (e.g., PZEM-004T) that track real-time power usage across different appliances or hours.
    
    \item \textbf{Smart Parking Subsystem:} Proximity, pressure, and ultrasonic sensors that detect vehicle presence, weight, and height to determine occupancy.
    
    \item \textbf{Contextual Sensors:} Ambient temperature and precipitation sensors used as features for both energy and parking models.
\end{itemize}


\noindent\textbf{2. Data Communication \& Edge Processing}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Edge Gateway:} A central microcontroller such as an ESP32 or Raspberry Pi that aggregates sensor data from multiple sensors.
    
    \item \textbf{Data Serialization:} Local cleaning and formatting of raw sensor readings into structured data frames compatible with Python-based machine learning models.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{3. AI Model \& Inference Layer (The Core)}

This layer hosts the predictive intelligence derived from trained machine learning models:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Energy Prediction Engine (Linear Regression):}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Preprocessing:} Loads the pre-trained \texttt{scaler.pkl} file to normalize real-time power consumption data.
        
        \item \textbf{Inference:} Uses the \texttt{Linear\_Regression\_model.pkl} to predict hourly energy consumption and estimate total energy usage between specific intervals (e.g., hours 3 to 6) to support load balancing.
    \end{itemize}
    
   
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{4. Application Logic \& Automation Layer}

This layer converts AI predictions into intelligent home automation actions:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Load Shedding Logic:} When the Energy Prediction Engine forecasts peak consumption, the system automatically dims non-essential lighting or schedules high-power appliances during lower-consumption periods.
    
    \item \textbf{Parking Orchestration:} If a parking violation is detected or a space becomes \textit{Vacant}, the system notifies the homeowner through a dashboard or mobile application.
\end{itemize}

\noindent\textbf{5. User Interface \& Reporting Layer}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Real-Time Dashboard:} Displays live energy consumption statistics (kWh) and real-time parking spot occupancy status.
    
    \item \textbf{Historical Analytics:} Utilizes stored historical data to generate analytical reports on energy savings and parking usage patterns for documentation and project evaluation.
\end{itemize}

% ---------------- Algorithm ----------------
\newpage
\section{Algorithm}
\subsection{Linear Regression for Energy Prediction}

\noindent


Linear Regression is a supervised machine learning algorithm used to predict a continuous value by establishing a linear relationship between independent variables (features) and a dependent variable (target).

In our system, Linear Regression is used to predict household energy consumption using sensor data such as temperature (DHT11), humidity, device usage status (light/fan ON--OFF), and time of operation.

The algorithm learns from historical data collected from the smart home and estimates how each feature affects electricity usage. After training, the model achieved approximately:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $R^2 = 0.6180$
    \item RMSE = 5.04
\end{itemize}

These performance metrics help the system monitor power usage and suggest energy-saving actions.

\subsection*{Mathematical Formula}

The basic Linear Regression equation is:

\begin{equation}
y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \beta_3 x_3 + \cdots + \beta_n x_n + \varepsilon
\end{equation}

Where:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $y$ = Predicted energy consumption
    \item $\beta_0$ = Intercept (constant value)
    \item $\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3, \dots, \beta_n$ = Model coefficients (weights)
    \item $x_1, x_2, x_3, \dots, x_n$ = Input features (temperature, humidity, device usage, time, etc.)
    \item $\varepsilon$ = Error (difference between actual and predicted value)
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cost Function (Error Minimization)}

Linear Regression finds the best fitting line by minimizing the Mean Squared Error (MSE):

\begin{equation}
\text{MSE} = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2
\end{equation}

Where:

\begin{itemize}
    \item $y_i$ = Actual energy consumption
    \item $\hat{y}_i$ = Predicted energy consumption
    \item $n$ = Number of observations
\end{itemize}





